Black Crappie

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Black Crappie
Pomoxis nigromaculatus

Common length: 5 - 12 inches

Found in brush during the spring and in open water during summer
Head, back, and sides are mottled with black blotches
Feed on plankton, aquatic insects, crustaceans, and small fish
Native to Ohio where they are a popular sport fish

  • Can be found in:
  • Gamefish Cylinder

Golden Shiner

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Golden Shiner
Notemigonus crysoleucas

Common length: 4 - 7 inches

Found in streams, natural wetlands, and lakes
Prefer clean, clear water with an abundance of aquatic vegetation
Deep bodied with silver-gold coloration
Feed on plant matter, snails, insects, and crustaceans

Brown Bullhead Catfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Brown Bullhead Catfish
Amerius nebulosus

Common length: 8- 16 inches

Largest and least common bullhead species in Ohio
Prefer deep, clear waters
Sharp spines on dorsal and pectoral fins
Build nests in natural cavities where females will lay eggs
At least one of the parents will guard the eggs until they hatch
Males guard the young after they hatch
Feed on fish, crayfish, and aquatic insects

  • Can be found in:
  • Ohio Gamefish

Channel Catfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Channel Catfish
Ictalurus punctatus

Common length: 15 - 25 inches

A popular sport and food fish
Found in large rivers and lakes throughout Ohio
Prefer areas with deep water, clean gravel, and low currents but tolerant of a wide range of conditions
Use natural cavities, such as undercut banks and burrows, as nests to lay eggs in
Scaleless and have a spine in the pectoral and dorsal fins
Eight barbels around the mouth are used for locating food
Omnivores, eat a variety of foods including insect larvae, crayfish, mollusks, fish, and some types of fruits

  • Can be found in:
  • Ohio Gamefish

An abundant sport fish in the United States, including Ohio
Distributed throughout Ohio in most bodies of water
Spawn in late spring or early summer

Build breeding nests in large colonies

Hybrid Striped Bass

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Hybrid Striped Bass
Morone chrysops saxatili

Common length is 12 - 30 inches

Hybrid of a female striped bass and a male white bass
Silver body with dark horizontal broken stripes
Ohio Division of Wildlife stocks this species for sport fishing

Green Sunfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Green Sunfish
Lepomis cyanellus

Maximum Length: 10inches, typically 3-7 inches

Tolerant of turbid (murky) waters
Dark olive green colored body with iridescent blue lines on their cheeks
Feeds on aquatic insect larvae, snails, crayfish, and some small fish
Considered to be very aggressive
Will often hybridize with other sunfish

  • Can be found in:
  • Sunfish

Bluebreast Darter

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Bluebreast Darter
Etheostoma camurum

Common length: 2-3 inches

In Ohio they are found in medium to large rivers only in the Ohio River Basin
An indicator of good water quality and stream habitat
Feed on insect larvae, crustaceans, and other aquatic invertebrates
Males guard a small territory around the spawning site until the eggs hatch
They bury their eggs in gravel in fast flowing riffles
Considered a threatened species in Ohio

  • Can be found in:
  • Darters

Rainbow Darter

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Rainbow Darter
Etheostoma caeruleum

Freshwater fish native to Ohio
Males have bright coloration with 8-13 blue bands that intensify during breeding season
Females have 8-13 brown bands and lack the bright coloration
Commonly found in medium to small sized streams where they prefer riffles and small cobble
Common length is 1.5-2.5 inches

  • Can be found in:
  • Darters

Spotted Turtle

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Spotted Turtle
Clemmys guttata

Black with yellow spots on the carapace and reddish-orange to yellow blotches on the head and chin
Found in small streams, marshes, bogs, and pond edges where vegetation is abundant
Often seen basking on the edge of water or on objects protruding out of the water
This turtle species is threatened in Ohio
Maximum size is 6 inches

  • Can be found in:
  • Spotted Turtle

Common Carp

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Common Carp
Cyprinus carpio

Maximum Length: 40 inches

Native to Europe and were first stocked in Ohio waters in 1879 as a food fish
Highly tolerant of poor water quality and have easily spread throughout Ohio
Have 2 barbels on each side of their mouth
Coloration is bronze gold to yellow
Brightly colored common carp are known as â€œkoiâ€ and commonly sold as ornamental fish for garden ponds
Eat a variety of items including insect larvae, crustaceans, mollusks, some aquatic plants, fish eggs, and even small fish

  • Can be found in:
  • Invasive Species of Ohio

Common Goldfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Common Goldfish
Carassius auratus

Maximum Length: 16 inches, typically 6-10 inches

Feed on invertebrates, some algae, and plant material
In the wild, most goldfish have a more natural color instead of a bright orange color
Goldfish show no parental care to young, they spawn by scattering eggs across vegetation
Are an invasive species to the United States
Native only to Asia
Invasive species are defined as non-native species to the ecosystem that creates a negative impact on our natural environment.
Human actions, such as travels, export shipping, or releasing exotic pets, are the primary reasons for invasive species to be introduced.

  • Can be found in:
  • Invasive Species of Ohio

Round Goby

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Round Goby
Neogobius melanostomus

Native to the Black and Caspian Seas in Eastern Europe
Probably came to the Great Lakes via ballast water from vessels
Can displace native fish by eating their eggs and young by taking over optimal habitat
Bottom dwelling fish with a fused pelvic fin and mottled coloration

  • Invasive Species of Ohio

Midland Painted Turtle

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Midland Painted Turtle
Chrysemys picta marginata

Have a deep green carapace with red and black along the marginal plates that look as though they have been individually painted
Widespread throughout North America
Seek deep water for winter hibernation
Lives in slow moving freshwaters
Adults can live for more than 55 years.
Are omnivores, eating plants, fish, tadpoles, and insects

  • Can be found in:
  • Midland Painted Turtle

Emerald Shiner

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Emerald Shiner
Notropis atherinoides

Maximum Size: 4 inches

Very abundant in Lake Erie and the Ohio River
Have silvery backs with an emerald green or blue hue
Feed on zooplankton, insect larvae, and small flying insects
Harvested and sold as bait for fishing, important forage for sport fish
Broadcast spawn in open waters, scatter their eggs and give no parental care

Up

Redside Dace

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Redside Dace
Clinostomus elongatus

The redside dace is a species of ray-finned fish in the Cyprinidae family, found in the United States and Canada. They are commonly found in small, clear, cool streams. They are unique among minnows, being the only species to routinely feed on flying insects by leaping from water. Thus, it acts as a conduit for nutrient transfers between terrestrial and aquatic environments. The species can be used as an ecosystem health indicator, as it is sensitive to environmental disturbances.

  • Can be found in:
  • Ohio River 1
  • Menu

  • Home

    Return to the home page.

  • Scanner

River Chub

Menu
Click to enlarge.

River Chub
Nocomis micropogon

A robust minnow, dark olivaceous above to dusky yellow below, with orange-red fins, large scales, a large slightly subterminal mouth, and a small barbel at the corners of the jaw. During the breeding season, sexually mature males develop pinkish-purple coloration, and swollen heads with tubercles between the eyes and snout tip.

  • Can be found in:
  • Ohio River 1

Southern Redbelly Dace

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Southern Redbelly Dace
Phoxinus erythrogaster

The Southern redbelly dace, is a North American species of temperate freshwater fish of the Cyprinidae family. The natural geographic range extends from Western New York to Minnesota, and south to Oklahoma, Arkansas, and Alabama.This fish prefers flowing pools of creeks and streams.The bellies of breeding males are entirely red.

Shovelnose Sturgeon

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Shovelnose Sturgeon
Scaphirhynchus platorynchus

Have armored plates rather than scales and a broad, flat snout that gives them their name
Females reach sexual maturity at 5 years and do not spawn every year
Were commonly found in the Ohio River until 1910 when the lock and dam systems were built; now are an endangered species
Common length is 18-30 inches

Boesemani Rainbow

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Boesemani Rainbow
Melanotaenia boesemani

Maximum Length: 4 inches

Half and Half coloration: Head and front are a bluish gray and posterior is an orange-red
Coloration can fade in captivity
Males have elongated dorsal fin rays and deeper bodies
Females have a broad dark mid lateral stripe accompanied by a series of narrow yellow or reddish-orange longitudinal stripes.
Found mainly in Lake Ayamaru but also Lake Hain and Lake Aytinjo in Indonesia

Up

Australian Side-Necked Turtle

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Australian Side-Necked Turtle
Chelodina longicollis

Maximum size: 7 inches (shell length)
Maximum weight: 2 pounds

Endemic to Eastern and South Eastern Australia

Lifespan is 31 - 37 years

Semi-aquatic, typically found in swamps, lakes, and slow-moving waterways and creeks

Carnivorous, feed on aquatic invertebrates, fish, tadpoles, crustaceans, plankton and carrion

Can emit a pungent musk to deter predators

Have good water storage abilities which allow them to go dormant under trees in forested habitats for long periods

Identified by a long narrow neck covered in short tubercles and a black to light brown oval carapace that contains a central groove

During times of breeding, males perform head bobbing and fast swimming in an attempt to gain the attention of females

  • Can be found in:
  • Australia Side-Necked Turtles
  • Menu

    Return to the home page.

White Cloud Mountain Minnow
Tanichthys albonubes

Native to White Cloud Mountain located a few miles north of the city of Guangzhou in China
Inhabits clear, slow moving brooks with thick weed growth where they feed on plankton and the larvae of aquatic insects

Archerfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Archerfish
Toxotes jaculatrix

Maximum size: 10 inches

Inhabit fresh and salt waters of Southeast Asia (India, New Guinea, Australia, Philippines, Southeast Asia, and Oceania)

Found in Mangrove swamps

Can survive in salt water and fresh water

Found at or near the top of the water column

Typically found in schools

Hunt by shooting insects out of the air with spouts of water from their mouth

Can shoot prey up to 4 feet away

Occasionally they will jump from the water to pick insects out of mid flight

Can control their vision so that they can see from water to air without refraction of water and air, eliminating distortions

  • Can be found in:
  • Asia Archerfish

Red-Bellied Piranha

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Red-Bellied Piranha
Pygocentrus nattereri

Inhabit fast flowing river systems in South America
A single row of sharp, interlocking teeth in both jaws are used for rapid puncture and shearing of prey
Average length is 8 - 15 inches
More than 30 different species of Piranha have been identified
Known for their voracious appetite for meat, but are actually omnivores
Feed on fish, snails, insects and aquatic plants occasionally eating larger mammals and birds
Form large schools and constantly compete for food
Predators include river dolphins, crocodiles, turtles, birds, larger fish, and humans

  • Can be found in:
  • Red Bellied Piranha

Yellow-Spotted Amazon River Turtle

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Yellow-Spotted Amazon River Turtle
Podocnemis unifilis

One of the largest South American river turtles
Have yellow spots on their head that disappear as they age
Females can be twice as large as males
Inhabit the Amazon River
Feed on fruits, plants, small fish, and invertebrates
Most active in mid-morning and afternoon
Groups of turtles can be seen basking on logs or stones in the middle of the river

  • Can be found in:
  • Amazon River

Commonly swim at an angle with their heads pointing down
Belong to the family Anostomidae (Headstanders)
Occur in rocky areas of rapidly flowing waters

Red Hook Silver Dollar

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Red Hook Silver Dollar
Myleus rubripinnis

Maximum size is 15 inches
Non-aggressive omnivores with powerful jaws
Name comes from the red curved anal fin with black edging
Prefers calm zones of main rivers where the vegetation hangs over the river banks.
Feeds on the leaves of river plants
Possesses powerful dentition that can cause serious bites.

  • Can be found in:
  • Amazon River

Uaru

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Uaru
Uaru amphiacanthoides

Native to the Amazon Basin region in Brazil and Guyana
Abundant in its native range
Young feed on the parentâ€™s slime coat
Adults are omnivores, feeding on detritus, plant material, insects, and crustaceans
Greenish brown with black along their sides
During spawning times, their bodies become all black and they get coppery red eyes
Females lay eggs on substrate or on a flat exhibit. Both male and female will guard the fish.
Maximum Length is 12 inches

  • Can be found in:
  • Amazon River

African Spurred Tortoise

Menu
Click to enlarge.

African Spurred Tortoise
Geochelone sulcata

Average Size: 20 inches and 70-100 pounds

Third largest land tortoise worldwide

Lifespan in the wild is 50 - 70 years

Found in Sub-Saharan Africa, across the countries of Burkina Faso, Chad, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Mali, Mauritania, Nigeria, Senegal and Sudan

Herbivores, feeding on wild grasses and plants in their native range.

In captivity they will feed on any vegetation available, here they get a variety of vegetables.

Males can be identified by having a concave plastron and anal scutes that are more flared or forked than females.

Common name refers to the well-defined spurs on the legs

In the 1990â€™s this species of tortoise became popular pets in the U.S. and as a result, captive raised animals became readily available to the public. They are now recognized as the most produced tortoise species in the world.

This boom in popularity was not accompanied with appropriate education for the new pet owners. Many found themselves quickly overwhelmed with the needs of housing and caring for such large and fast growing animals.

An overpopulation of this species has occurred at rescue facilities around the country as pet owners have tried to get rid of their once small tortoises.


*Our tortoises are rescue animals from Noahâ€™s Lost Ark, an exotic animal sanctuary that provides a permanent and safe home to unwanted and abused animals

  • Can be found in:
  • African Spurred Tortoise

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Daffodil Cichlid
Neolamprologus pulcher

Maximum Length: 3 inches

Endemic to Lake Tanganyika in Africa
Have an omnivorous diet
Breed in pairs, the male and female both defend the territory and young
Spawn in caves, eggs are deposited into cracks and crevices
Males have elongated fin tips and a hump on their forehead

  • Lake Tanganyika

Up

Lionfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Lionfish
Pterois volitans

Found in the Indian and Western Pacific oceans
Characterized by red, white and black bands, showy pectoral fins and venomous spines
Spines contain venom which is used as a defense mechanism
Aggressively prey on small fish and invertebrates as they hide in crevices and then ambush prey as it swims past
Predators of the lionfish are larger fish, eels, and humans
Live up to 15 years
In the mid 1990s two species were unintentionally introduced into the Atlantic Ocean and have become an invasive species along the East Coast of the United States

  • Can be found in:
  • Lionfish

Queensland Grouper
Epinephelus lanceolatus

Carnivorous, feeding on lobsters, crabs, bony fish, and small sharks
Considered vulnerable to extinction as a result of overfishing
Thought to be of great medicinal value and to bring good luck in Southeast Asia

Up

Green Chromis

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Green Chromis
Chromis Viridis

Found in the Indo-Pacific region
Males build nests in sand and rubble during breeding season. Multiple females will lay their eggs in one males nest. The male guards the eggs until they hatch.
Males that are guarding nests change their color to yellow
Adults are found in schools above branching corals in subtidal reef flats and lagoons
Juveniles stay close to individual corals
They feed on phytoplankton

  • Can be found in:
  • Indo-Pacific Reef

Saddleback Butterflyfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Saddleback Butterflyfish
Chaetodon ephippium

Found in the Indo-Pacific region
Overall coloration is yellowish-grey with a large black spot bordered below by a white band on the back and wavy blue lines on the lower sides
Adults have a filament extending from the upper part of the front portion of the dorsal fin
Found in lagoons and seaward reefs where they prefer coral-rich and clear water areas
Adults are often found in pairs and juveniles are found solitary
Feed on algae, small invertebrates, coral polyps and fish eggs
Maximum length is 12 inches

  • Indo-Pacific Lagoon

Blue Boxfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Blue Boxfish
Ostracion meleagris

Maximum Length: 6 inches

Boxfish belong to the Ostraciidae family.
Inhabit the waters of the Indo-Pacific region, usually clear lagoons and seaweed reefs
Males swim about more openly than females which are often in close vicinity to the males. They are commonly found in solitude
Exhibit sexual dimorphism, females and juveniles are brown or green with white spots. Large males are blue with orange spots or bands.
A boxfishesâ€™ scales form hexagonal bony plates that are fused together to form a rigid body case that is bell shaped and inflexible.
Only the eyes, jaws, and fins are mobile
Feed on tunicates, polychaetes, sponges, mollusks, copepods, and algae.

  • Can be found in:
  • Hawaiian Fish

Named for the way they appear to look down their noses

Up

Bahama Sea Star

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Bahama Sea Star
Oreaster reticulatus

Maximum Length: 19.5 inches

Use water pressure for circulation, instead of blood

Are able to regurgitate their stomachs out of their mouths in order to digest large prey items

Lay a large amount of buoyant eggs in water currents, external fertilization occurs

Live in solitude

Active during the day, using thousands of tube feet to move about 0.12-0.33 m per minute.

Ranges from South Carolina to the Caribbean

Distinguished from other species by their hard shell and short tapered arms

Coloration can range from brown and red to orange and yellow.

Juveniles are green, this provides camouflage from predators

If food availability is low, they can re-absorb their own tissue leading to a reduction in size

Can sense light and dark through a microscopic eye called an ocellus

Feed on small invertebrates such as copepods, crab larvae, sponge tissue, and worms.

  • Can be found in:
  • Echinoderms
  • Touch Pool Invertibrates

  • Home

    Return to the home page.

  • Scanner

    Scan a QR code to go directly to an exhibit's page.

Lined Seahorse

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Lined Seahorse
Hippocampus erectus

Maximum size: 8 inches

Found in shallow seagrass beds, coral reefs, and floating sargassum from Nova Scotia to Argentina and throughout the Gulf of Mexico
Swim upright by rapidly fluttering a small fin on their back
Tails curl around the vegetation or coral branches to anchor them in place and conserve energy
Do not have stomachs, so they eat frequently using their tubular snout to suck in tiny crustaceans
Monogamous species pairing for life
One of the few species where the males become pregnant and give birth

  • Can be found in:
  • Seahorses

Upside Down Jellyfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Upside Down Jellyfish
Cassiopea xamachana

  • The bell is positioned downwards while the tentacles are upwards in the water column
  • Found on the bottom of inshore bays and mangrove forests throughout the Caribbean Sea, Gulf of Mexico, Hawaii and Indo-Pacific Oceans
  • Lifecycle consists of four phases, which are larva, polyp, ephyra, and medusa
  • Nematocysts, or stinging cells, cover the tentacles and are used for both feeding and defense
  • Maximum width is 12 inches

  • Can be found in:
  • Upside-Down Jellyfish

Clown Anemonefish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Clown Anemonefish
Amphiprion ocellaris

Maximum length: 4 inches

Bright orange with three white vertical bars
Found in the Indian Ocean, Red Sea, and Western Pacific
Share a symbiotic relationship with sea anemones. The sea anemone protects the clownfish from predators and the
A slime coating protects them from the stinging tentacles of the sea anemone
All clownfish develop first into males and then possibly into females later.
An adult male and female may reside on the same anemone with several juveniles. If the female dies, the largest male will transform into a female.
Females control males with aggressive dominance
Monogamous, mate for life
Males guard and aerate the eggs which adhere to substrate

  • Can be found in:
  • Live Coral
  • Hermit Crab

Red Grouper

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Red Grouper
Epinephelus morio

The scientific genus name â€œEpinephelusâ€ is derived from the Greek word â€œepinephelosâ€ meaning cloudy
Common throughout the Atlantic Ocean from North Carolina so Southern Brazil including the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean Sea.
Found in areas with muddy and rocky bottom habitats where they rest on the bottom substrate.
The head and body are dark reddish brown in color with light colored blotches and spots scattered on the body
Groupers have several sets of strong, slender teeth that are used to prevent small fish from escaping instead of tearing flesh
Prey items include crabs, shrimp, octopi, and small fish
Known to ambush prey and swallow it whole
Females reach sexual maturity at 4-6 years and males at 10 years of age.
Can reach up to 51 pounds and have a lifespan of 25-30 years.
A protogynous hermaphrodite, all fish start life as females with most transforming to males between the ages of 7-14 years.
Spawning occurs from January to April in the Gulf of Mexico and Caribbean Sea.
Eggs and sperm are released into offshore waters where fertilized eggs will float on the waterâ€™s surface
Predators include sharks and barracudas

  • Cave Exhibit

Up

Green Moray Eel

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Green Moray Eel
Gymnothorax funebris

Maximum length is 72 inches

Can weigh up to 30 pounds
Move by undulating their flattened bodies into lateral waves
Are constantly opening and closing their mouths to force water over the gills
Commonly found in shallow, rocky shorelines, reefs, and mangroves in the western Atlantic from New Jersey to Brazil.
Have scale free skin that is bathed in a protective, yellowy mucus that tints them green and protects them from parasites and diseases
Often hide in rock crevices and caves where they hide from predators and wait for unsuspecting prey.
Are able to tie themselves in knots to gain leverage for tearing prey
Hunt at night and feed on crabs, cephalopods, shrimps, and fishes
Rely on their keen sense of smell to locate prey
They have 2 rows of single cuspid teeth on the front of their upper jaw and one row in the back and along the lower jaw. The roof of the mouth has 2 rows of teeth.
Eels are oviparous, meaning they produce eggs that hatch outside of the body.

  • Can be found in:
  • Cave Exhibit
  • SeaTube

Up

Atlantic Stingray

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Atlantic Stingray
Dasyatis sabina

Maximum width is 14 inches
Found in the warm, shallow waters and estuaries of the western Atlantic Ocean and Gulf of Mexico
Prefer areas with sand or silt bottoms where they can bury themselves and hide from predators.
Able to tolerate a variety of salinities; some populations reside in freshwaters
Brown to yellowish in color with an extended snout
Have 2 tail spines with venom being produced in the narrow grooves of the spine
Have multiple rows with flat, blunt surfaces
Feed on benthic invertebrates including crustaceans and mollusks
Highly electroreceptive, use Ampullae of Lorenzini to detect weak electric fields given off by prey items.
Mating season is between October and April with females giving live birth to 1-4 pups
Have a lifespan of 9 years
Predators include sharks. Freshwater populations may be preyed upon by alligators
Temperature induced seasonal migrations have been observed

  • Can be found in:
  • Touch Pool Vertibrates
  • Menu

  • Home

Up

Cownose Stingray

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Cownose Stingray
Rhinopera bonasus

Common disc width is 24-31 inches
Found in the Eastern Atlantic Ocean from Mauritania to Guinea off of the coast of Africa. Also found in the Western Atlantic from southern New England to northern Florida and Gulf of Mexico migrating to Trinidad, Venezuela, and Brazil.
Often stay at the top of the water column and make migrations to different parts of the ocean. They migrate northward in the late spring and southward in the late fall.
It is believed that changes in water temperature and sun orientation may initiate seasonal mass migration.
Identified by the indented anterior contour of their cartilaginous skull
May have one or two tail spines. The first spine is located directly behind the base of the dorsal fin. The second spine is not always present.
The spine processes toxins and mucous into its ventral grooves, which is produced from spongy venom glands located along the underside of the spine.
Usually have 7 series of teeth
Feed on bivalve mollusks. They can crush the shells between their tooth plates.
Have smooth skin
Belong to the Elasmobranch family. Bodies are made up of cartilage instead of bones.
Breeding period is considered to be from June through October with gestation believing to last between 11-12 months.
Development is ovoviviparous-eggs are produced internally, develop within the maternal body and hatch within. It is suspected that only one embryo will usually be carried to full term, but there have been recordings of females carrying more to term.
Some predators of cownose rays include cobia, sandbar sharks, and bull sharks

  • Can be found in:
  • Touch Pool Vertibrates
  • SeaTube

Southern Stingray

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Southern Stingray
Dasyatis americana

Maximum Length is 79 inches.
Benthic or bottom dwelling animals that can be found in shallow coastal waters with sandy bottoms.
Found in tropical waters of the Atlantic Ocean, Caribbean, and the Gulf of Mexico. Most abundant in Florida and the Bahamas
Are gray to brown in color that can weigh up to 214 lbs.
Feed on crustaceans, mollusks, and bony fish
Gestation is between 4-11 months with females giving live birth to an average litter size of 4 pups.
There is a direct correlation between the size of the female and the litter size
Occasionally preyed on by sharks
Feed by slowly grazing along the sandy ocean floor, relying on electro-reception combined with a strong sense of smell and touch.

  • Touch Pool Vertibrates

Bahama Sea Star

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Bahama Sea Star
Oreaster reticulatus

Maximum Length: 19.5 inches

Use water pressure for circulation, instead of blood

Are able to regurgitate their stomachs out of their mouths in order to digest large prey items

Lay a large amount of buoyant eggs in water currents, external fertilization occurs

Live in solitude

Active during the day, using thousands of tube feet to move about 0.12-0.33 m per minute.

Ranges from South Carolina to the Caribbean

Distinguished from other species by their hard shell and short tapered arms

Coloration can range from brown and red to orange and yellow.

Juveniles are green, this provides camouflage from predators

If food availability is low, they can re-absorb their own tissue leading to a reduction in size

Can sense light and dark through a microscopic eye called an ocellus

Feed on small invertebrates such as copepods, crab larvae, sponge tissue, and worms.

  • Can be found in:
  • Echinoderms
  • Touch Pool Invertibrates

Oyster Toadfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Oyster Toadfish
Osparius tau

Maximum length: 12 inches

Has a scaleless, flattened body that is olive-brown, black with dark blotches and bars.
Fleshy flaps or whiskers on cheeks and jaws
Can tolerate litter and polluted water, and can survive out of water for a lengthy period of time.
Defends itself from predators with strong, broad jaws, full of rounded teeth and a spiny dorsal fin.
A bottom dweller found primarily around oyster reefs, it can also be found in wrecks, debris, vegetation, and other dark spots in shallow waters in warmer weather
In cooler months it moves into the deep channels of the Chesapeake Bay.

Porkfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Porkfish
Anisotremus virginicus

Maximum length: 15 inches

Commonly found in the Atlantic Ocean from Florida to Brazil
Nocturnal
Often found in schools inhabiting shallow inshore waters over reefs and rocky bottoms
Make a grunting sound by rubbing their teeth together
Has yellow fins and 2 black bars, one of which runs diagonally through the eye
Adults feed on invertebrates such as mollusks, echinoderms, and worms.
Juveniles pick parasites from the skin and scales of other species of fish, and are considered "cleaners".

Up

Gulf Flounder

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Gulf Flounder
Paralichthys albigutta

Maximum size: 71 cm

Flounder swim sideways which makes it easier for them to bury themselves with a thin layer of sand. They use a fluttering motion to do this.
Flounder camouflage themselves in the sand but have 3 eye-like spots on their side that form a triangle.
Both of the gulf flounderâ€™s eyes are on the same side of its body. This feature allows it to stay buried flat in the sand while also looking for prey.
It hatches into a usual fish form, but the right eye eventually migrates over to the left side.
They are predators who lie on the sandy bottom, waiting for a small prey species to come by. By having both eyes on one side of the head, a degree of depth perception is generated that enables them to swim up and capture the prey. The upper side of the fish, on which the eyes are found, is dark-colored, to match the bottom, but the underside is whitish-pink. And there are "right-eyed" and "left-eyed" flounders, depending on which side of the head the eyes migrate to!

  • Can be found in:
  • Rock Pool

    Return to the home page.

Blacknose Shark

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Blacknose Shark
Carcharhinus acronotus

Maximum length is 55 inches

The blacknose shark is found in the Atlantic Ocean from North Carolina to Southern Brazil including the Caribbean Sea and Gulf of Mexico.
An inshore species, they are often found in waters of continental shelves over sandy and coral bottoms.
Juveniles are typically found in shallow water while adults are located at greater depths (over 30ft)
Known to form large schools
They get their name from the characteristic black or dusky spot under the tip of the snout.
Both sexes reach maturity at 2 years of age and 3-3.5 feet in length.
Mate in late May/ early June and have a 10-11 month gestation period.
Feed on small fishes such as porgies, anchovies, spiny boxfishes, and porcupine fish.

Sand Tiger Shark

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Sand Tiger Shark
Carcharias taurus

Maximum length is 10.5 feet
Common throughout the world, except in the Eastern Pacific
Found inshore extending to a variety of areas including the surf zone, shallow bays, coral and rocky reefs, and deeper areas around the outer continental shelves
Migrate within its region, moving north during the summer and towards the equator in the fall and winter months
A large, bulky shark that is generally light brown or light greenish-gray above and grayish white below.
Some have darker reddish or brown spots scattered on the body
Have 44 to 48 upper teeth and 41 to 46 lower teeth.
Males maturity is reached at 6.3 feet and at 4 to 5 years of age. Females maturity is reached at 6 years and lengths over 7.2 feet.
Feed on a wide variety of small bony fish
Ovoviviparous. Usually only one pup will survive in each uteri because the largest embryo ends up eating all of its smaller siblings during gestation.
Gestation is believed to be around 8 to 9 months long, pups are 39 inches in length at birth
Mature individuals have no major predators
Sand tiger sharks do not have swim bladders. Because of this, they will come to the surface and take in gulps of air, which it holds in its stomach. This allows the shark to hover motionless in the water.
Observations have shown that this shark is not aggressive unless provoked. Their jagged teeth make them look fiercer than they actually are.
Currently sand tiger sharks are regulated on the east coast of the United States where it is identified as a prohibited species. Any sand tiger caught must be immediately released with minimal harm to the shark.

Sandbar Shark

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Sandbar Shark
Carcharhinus plumbeus

Maximum length is 7.5 feet.
Inhabits temperate and tropical waters around the globe.
The most abundant species of large shark in the Western Atlantic
Found in shallow coastal waters where they are bottom dwellers and rarely seen at the waterâ€™s surface
Undergo seasonal migrations that are influenced by temperature and possibly ocean currents.
Distinguished by its taller than average first dorsal fin
Can reach up to 7.5 feet but typically grow to only 6 feet
Can weigh from 100-200 pounds, typically males reach 110 pounds and females reach 150 pounds
An opportunistic bottom-feeder that preys primarily on relatively small fishes, mollusks, and crustaceans.
Feed throughout the day, but more active at night.
In the northern hemisphere, mating occurs in the spring or early summer. In the southern hemisphere, mating occurs in late October to January.
The gestation period can range from 8-12 months depending on geographical location.
Litter size correlates with the size of the female
Juveniles may fall prey to larger sharks. Adults have few if any predators
Sandbar sharks play an important role in commercial fishery along the eastern United States. Because of this, they are vulnerable to over-exploitation by fishing.

Cownose Stingray

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Cownose Stingray
Rhinopera bonasus

Common disc width is 24-31 inches
Found in the Eastern Atlantic Ocean from Mauritania to Guinea off of the coast of Africa. Also found in the Western Atlantic from southern New England to northern Florida and Gulf of Mexico migrating to Trinidad, Venezuela, and Brazil.
Often stay at the top of the water column and make migrations to different parts of the ocean. They migrate northward in the late spring and southward in the late fall.
It is believed that changes in water temperature and sun orientation may initiate seasonal mass migration.
Identified by the indented anterior contour of their cartilaginous skull
May have one or two tail spines. The first spine is located directly behind the base of the dorsal fin. The second spine is not always present.
The spine processes toxins and mucous into its ventral grooves, which is produced from spongy venom glands located along the underside of the spine.
Usually have 7 series of teeth
Feed on bivalve mollusks. They can crush the shells between their tooth plates.
Have smooth skin
Belong to the Elasmobranch family. Bodies are made up of cartilage instead of bones.
Breeding period is considered to be from June through October with gestation believing to last between 11-12 months.
Development is ovoviviparous-eggs are produced internally, develop within the maternal body and hatch within. It is suspected that only one embryo will usually be carried to full term, but there have been recordings of females carrying more to term.
Some predators of cownose rays include cobia, sandbar sharks, and bull sharks

  • Touch Pool Vertibrates

Southern Stingray

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Southern Stingray
Dasyatis americana

Maximum Length is 79 inches.
Benthic or bottom dwelling animals that can be found in shallow coastal waters with sandy bottoms.
Found in tropical waters of the Atlantic Ocean, Caribbean, and the Gulf of Mexico. Most abundant in Florida and the Bahamas
Are gray to brown in color that can weigh up to 214 lbs.
Feed on crustaceans, mollusks, and bony fish
Gestation is between 4-11 months with females giving live birth to an average litter size of 4 pups.
There is a direct correlation between the size of the female and the litter size
Occasionally preyed on by sharks
Feed by slowly grazing along the sandy ocean floor, relying on electro-reception combined with a strong sense of smell and touch.

Red Grouper

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Red Grouper
Epinephelus morio

The scientific genus name â€œEpinephelusâ€ is derived from the Greek word â€œepinephelosâ€ meaning cloudy
Common throughout the Atlantic Ocean from North Carolina so Southern Brazil including the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean Sea.
Found in areas with muddy and rocky bottom habitats where they rest on the bottom substrate.
The head and body are dark reddish brown in color with light colored blotches and spots scattered on the body
Groupers have several sets of strong, slender teeth that are used to prevent small fish from escaping instead of tearing flesh
Prey items include crabs, shrimp, octopi, and small fish
Known to ambush prey and swallow it whole
Females reach sexual maturity at 4-6 years and males at 10 years of age.
Can reach up to 51 pounds and have a lifespan of 25-30 years.
A protogynous hermaphrodite, all fish start life as females with most transforming to males between the ages of 7-14 years.
Spawning occurs from January to April in the Gulf of Mexico and Caribbean Sea.
Eggs and sperm are released into offshore waters where fertilized eggs will float on the waterâ€™s surface
Predators include sharks and barracudas

Rock Hind Grouper

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Rock Hind Grouper
Epinephelus adscensionis

Maximum length is 24 inches while common length is 14 inches

Common in the western Atlantic from Massachusetts to Brazil including the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean and in the eastern Atlantic down the coast of Africa.
Usually found in solitude inhabiting rocky reefs.
Feed on crabs and fishes in the western Atlantic and on baby sea turtles and triggerfish in the eastern Atlantic
Coloration is tan with red spots on the head, body, and fins with the spots becoming larger ventrally
A powerful suction is created when they open their mouths, easily sucking in prey items and swallowing them whole
Like other groupers, all begin life as females and change to males as they mature.

Blue Angelfish
Holacanthus bermudensis

Maximum length: 18 inches

Benthic fish, they stay near the bottom to feed on sponges, corals, and algae
Can hybridize with Queen Angelfish
Juveniles set up â€œcleaning stationsâ€, picking parasites off of larger fish
Common in the tropical parts of the Western Atlantic and the Gulf of Mexico
Have small protractile mouths and comb like teeth
Moves around the reef during the day and sleeps hidden away at night
Has a blue smudge on its forehead and a blue caudal (tail) fin bordered in yellow
Adults are generally found in pairs year round, suggesting a monogamous relationship between the male and the female

French Angelfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

French Angelfish
Pomacanthus paru

Maximum length is 24 inches while common length is 16 inches

Commonly found in the western Atlantic Ocean from Florida and the Bahamas, south to Brazil including the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean Sea.
Usually found at depths less than 15 feet in coral reef areas.
Have small mouths with comb-like teeth
Their scales are black and rimmed with a bright golden yellow. They have black fins with yellow bars at the base of the pectoral fins, yellow rimmed eyes, and a white chin
Juveniles are dark brown to black with three thick vertical yellow bands that continue onto the fins.
Angelfish may live up to 10 years
Sexual maturity is reached at lengths of 10 inches
Feed on a wide range of algae and invertebrates
Juveniles feed on algae and detritus along with ectoparasites they clean from other fishes.
Tend â€œcleaning stationsâ€ where they remove ectoparasites from a wide range of fishes including jacks, snappers, morays, grunts, surgeonfishes, and wrasses.
Spawning occurs from April through September over deep reef areas in the early morning hours. During each event, approximately 25,000-75,000 eggs are released.
The eggs are pelagic
Large fish are potential predators

Green Moray Eel

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Green Moray Eel
Gymnothorax funebris

Maximum length is 72 inches

Can weigh up to 30 pounds
Move by undulating their flattened bodies into lateral waves
Are constantly opening and closing their mouths to force water over the gills
Commonly found in shallow, rocky shorelines, reefs, and mangroves in the western Atlantic from New Jersey to Brazil.
Have scale free skin that is bathed in a protective, yellowy mucus that tints them green and protects them from parasites and diseases
Often hide in rock crevices and caves where they hide from predators and wait for unsuspecting prey.
Are able to tie themselves in knots to gain leverage for tearing prey
Hunt at night and feed on crabs, cephalopods, shrimps, and fishes
Rely on their keen sense of smell to locate prey
They have 2 rows of single cuspid teeth on the front of their upper jaw and one row in the back and along the lower jaw. The roof of the mouth has 2 rows of teeth.
Eels are oviparous, meaning they produce eggs that hatch outside of the body.

Bluestriped Grunt

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Bluestriped Grunt
Haemulon sciurus


Maximum length is 18 inches
Found in the western Atlantic Ocean from South Carolina to Brazil. This includes the Gulf of Mexico and Caribbean Sea.
Common in mangroves, reefs, and seagrass beds
Known to occasionally face and push one another with open mouths. The purpose of this behavior is unknown but it may be related to courtship or territory defense.
Named for the pig-like grunts produced with their well-developed pharyngeal teeth located in the throat. They grind the teeth together to produce the sound which is amplified by the taut air bladder
Feed on crustaceans, bivalves, and various small fishes
Spawn during the months of January-April in the Caribbean Sea.

French Grunt

Menu
Click to enlarge.

French Grunt
Haemulon flavolineatum

Maximum length is 11.8 inches while common length is 6.7 inches

Commonly found in the western Atlantic Ocean off Bermuda, South Carolina and the northern Gulf of Mexico to Brazil
Occur in large schools over rocky substrate, coral reefs, under ledges or close to elkhorn coral.
Juveniles are commonly found in bays and lagoons where they can find protection in sea grass beds
Identified from other grunts because they are the only grunt that has enlarged scales below the lateral line
Coloration is white to bluish with bright yellow to orange stripes. The first 3 stripes are straight, with the stripes below the lateral line being diagonal
All grunts are able to grind their teeth together to produce a grunting noise that is amplified by the swim bladder
Feeds primarily on small crustaceans, polychaetes, and mollusks
Considered a nocturnal species, scavenges sea beds at night.
Predators include trumpetfish, black grouper, and Nassau grouper

Caranx crysos

Inhabit the Eastern Atlantic including the western Mediterranean and the Western Atlantic from Canada to Brazil, including the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean
Often found in schools not far from the coast
Juveniles are found in association with floating Sargassum
They feed on fishes, shrimps, and other invertebrates
An excellent food fish and often used for bait

Crevalle Jack

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Crevalle Jack
Caranx hippos

Maximum length is 39.8 inches
Found in the coastal areas of the western Atlantic Ocean from Nova Scotia to Uruguay and the Gulf of Mexico.
Found in oceans, estuaries, and rivers.
Larval and juveniles are found in upstream currents and are common in shallow brackish waters.
Adults occupy upstream currents, reefs, offshore areas or shallow inshore areas.
Identified by their scaleless chest with a small patch of scales in front of the pelvic fins and an oval black spot on the pectoral fins
Juveniles have 5 dark bars on their bodies until the reach about 6.5 inches.
Adults are greenish-bluish above and silvery white to yellowish or golden below.
Make a croaking sound when out of the water by grinding their upper and lower teeth together.
Feed on a variety of fish, shrimp, and invertebrates.
Spawn in early March to early September in the southeastern Atlantic coast and in the Gulf Stream.
Predators include surface feeding carnivores such as the striped marlin and sea birds.

Dusky Squirrelfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Dusky Squirrelfish
Sargocentron vexillarium

Maximum length is 7 inches
Inhabit inshore reefs and tide pools in the Western Atlantic from Florida down to South America
Often found hiding in small recesses
Feed on various crustaceans
Common, but they are rarely seen because they are nocturnal
Reproduce by external fertilization and do not provide parental care
Typically they have two breeding seasons per year

Lookdown

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Lookdown
Selene vomer

Maximum length is 16 inches
Have a very blunt forehead and an extremely deep and laterally compressed body with very small, embedded scales
Coloration is iridescent silvery to golden with a metallic bluish tinge on the dorsal side
Occur in shallow coastal waters over sand or mud in the western Atlantic from Maine to Uruguay, including Bermuda
Travel in schools
Feed near the bottom on crustaceans and other fishes
Named for the way they appear to look down their noses

Maximum length: 36 inches

Can puff up to 2 times their normal size by sucking in water
Flesh contains a poison known as tetrodotoxin
Teeth are fused together creating crushing plates

Rooster Hogfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Rooster Hogfish
Lachnolaimus maximus

Maximum length is 36 inches
Commonly found in the Western Atlantic from North Carolina down to the north coast of South America, including the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean Sea
Commonly found over open bottoms and coral reefs and prefers locations with hard sand and rock bottoms near shallow patch reefs.
Get their name from their elongate, pig-like snout and large protrusible mouth that it uses to root around the bottom substrate for prey.
Generally, coloration is from pearl white to mottled in brownish-red with a black spot at the rear base of the soft dorsal fin and a bright red iris.
Males tend to be more intensely colored.
Have strong jaws and protruding anterior canine teeth
These teeth are adapted for crushing the shells of prey items such as mollusks and crabs
Have been known to live for up to 11 years
Hogfish are protogynous hermaphrodites. Females can transform into fully functioning males after they reach a mature size
Hogfish schools consist of groups of females dominated by a larger male, referred to as a harem. The male guards his harem and spawns exclusively with the females within it.
Spawning usually occurs in later afternoon and early evening.
Males and females release gametes into the surrounding water where they are fertilized.
Predators include larger bony fish and sharks

  • Can be found in:
  • SeaTube

Clown Anemonefish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Clown Anemonefish
Amphiprion ocellaris

Maximum length: 4 inches

Bright orange with three white vertical bars
Found in the Indian Ocean, Red Sea, and Western Pacific
Share a symbiotic relationship with sea anemones. The sea anemone protects the clownfish from predators and the
A slime coating protects them from the stinging tentacles of the sea anemone
All clownfish develop first into males and then possibly into females later.
An adult male and female may reside on the same anemone with several juveniles. If the female dies, the largest male will transform into a female.
Females control males with aggressive dominance
Monogamous, mate for life
Males guard and aerate the eggs which adhere to substrate

  • Can be found in:
  • Live Coral
  • Hermit Crab

Blacknose Shark

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Blacknose Shark
Carcharhinus acronotus

Maximum length is 55 inches

The blacknose shark is found in the Atlantic Ocean from North Carolina to Southern Brazil including the Caribbean Sea and Gulf of Mexico.
An inshore species, they are often found in waters of continental shelves over sandy and coral bottoms.
Juveniles are typically found in shallow water while adults are located at greater depths (over 30ft)
Known to form large schools
They get their name from the characteristic black or dusky spot under the tip of the snout.
Both sexes reach maturity at 2 years of age and 3-3.5 feet in length.
Mate in late May/ early June and have a 10-11 month gestation period.
Feed on small fishes such as porgies, anchovies, spiny boxfishes, and porcupine fish.

Sand Tiger Shark

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Sand Tiger Shark
Carcharias taurus

Maximum length is 10.5 feet
Common throughout the world, except in the Eastern Pacific
Found inshore extending to a variety of areas including the surf zone, shallow bays, coral and rocky reefs, and deeper areas around the outer continental shelves
Migrate within its region, moving north during the summer and towards the equator in the fall and winter months
A large, bulky shark that is generally light brown or light greenish-gray above and grayish white below.
Some have darker reddish or brown spots scattered on the body
Have 44 to 48 upper teeth and 41 to 46 lower teeth.
Males maturity is reached at 6.3 feet and at 4 to 5 years of age. Females maturity is reached at 6 years and lengths over 7.2 feet.
Feed on a wide variety of small bony fish
Ovoviviparous. Usually only one pup will survive in each uteri because the largest embryo ends up eating all of its smaller siblings during gestation.
Gestation is believed to be around 8 to 9 months long, pups are 39 inches in length at birth
Mature individuals have no major predators
Sand tiger sharks do not have swim bladders. Because of this, they will come to the surface and take in gulps of air, which it holds in its stomach. This allows the shark to hover motionless in the water.
Observations have shown that this shark is not aggressive unless provoked. Their jagged teeth make them look fiercer than they actually are.
Currently sand tiger sharks are regulated on the east coast of the United States where it is identified as a prohibited species. Any sand tiger caught must be immediately released with minimal harm to the shark.

  • SeaTube

Sandbar Shark

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Sandbar Shark
Carcharhinus plumbeus

Maximum length is 7.5 feet.
Inhabits temperate and tropical waters around the globe.
The most abundant species of large shark in the Western Atlantic
Found in shallow coastal waters where they are bottom dwellers and rarely seen at the waterâ€™s surface
Undergo seasonal migrations that are influenced by temperature and possibly ocean currents.
Distinguished by its taller than average first dorsal fin
Can reach up to 7.5 feet but typically grow to only 6 feet
Can weigh from 100-200 pounds, typically males reach 110 pounds and females reach 150 pounds
An opportunistic bottom-feeder that preys primarily on relatively small fishes, mollusks, and crustaceans.
Feed throughout the day, but more active at night.
In the northern hemisphere, mating occurs in the spring or early summer. In the southern hemisphere, mating occurs in late October to January.
The gestation period can range from 8-12 months depending on geographical location.
Litter size correlates with the size of the female
Juveniles may fall prey to larger sharks. Adults have few if any predators
Sandbar sharks play an important role in commercial fishery along the eastern United States. Because of this, they are vulnerable to over-exploitation by fishing.

Atlantic Stingray

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Atlantic Stingray
Dasyatis sabina

Maximum width is 14 inches
Found in the warm, shallow waters and estuaries of the western Atlantic Ocean and Gulf of Mexico
Prefer areas with sand or silt bottoms where they can bury themselves and hide from predators.
Able to tolerate a variety of salinities; some populations reside in freshwaters
Brown to yellowish in color with an extended snout
Have 2 tail spines with venom being produced in the narrow grooves of the spine
Have multiple rows with flat, blunt surfaces
Feed on benthic invertebrates including crustaceans and mollusks
Highly electroreceptive, use Ampullae of Lorenzini to detect weak electric fields given off by prey items.
Mating season is between October and April with females giving live birth to 1-4 pups
Have a lifespan of 9 years
Predators include sharks. Freshwater populations may be preyed upon by alligators
Temperature induced seasonal migrations have been observed

Cownose Stingray

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Cownose Stingray
Rhinopera bonasus

Common disc width is 24-31 inches
Found in the Eastern Atlantic Ocean from Mauritania to Guinea off of the coast of Africa. Also found in the Western Atlantic from southern New England to northern Florida and Gulf of Mexico migrating to Trinidad, Venezuela, and Brazil.
Often stay at the top of the water column and make migrations to different parts of the ocean. They migrate northward in the late spring and southward in the late fall.
It is believed that changes in water temperature and sun orientation may initiate seasonal mass migration.
Identified by the indented anterior contour of their cartilaginous skull
May have one or two tail spines. The first spine is located directly behind the base of the dorsal fin. The second spine is not always present.
The spine processes toxins and mucous into its ventral grooves, which is produced from spongy venom glands located along the underside of the spine.
Usually have 7 series of teeth
Feed on bivalve mollusks. They can crush the shells between their tooth plates.
Have smooth skin
Belong to the Elasmobranch family. Bodies are made up of cartilage instead of bones.
Breeding period is considered to be from June through October with gestation believing to last between 11-12 months.
Development is ovoviviparous-eggs are produced internally, develop within the maternal body and hatch within. It is suspected that only one embryo will usually be carried to full term, but there have been recordings of females carrying more to term.
Some predators of cownose rays include cobia, sandbar sharks, and bull sharks

  • Touch Pool Vertibrates
  • SeaTube

Southern Stingray

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Southern Stingray
Dasyatis americana

Maximum Length is 79 inches.
Benthic or bottom dwelling animals that can be found in shallow coastal waters with sandy bottoms.
Found in tropical waters of the Atlantic Ocean, Caribbean, and the Gulf of Mexico. Most abundant in Florida and the Bahamas
Are gray to brown in color that can weigh up to 214 lbs.
Feed on crustaceans, mollusks, and bony fish
Gestation is between 4-11 months with females giving live birth to an average litter size of 4 pups.
There is a direct correlation between the size of the female and the litter size
Occasionally preyed on by sharks
Feed by slowly grazing along the sandy ocean floor, relying on electro-reception combined with a strong sense of smell and touch.

A common fish that is often marketed for food
The sides of their body have rectangular dark gray blotches

Prefer coral reefs and clear water

Males are known to be territorial
Feed mainly on small fishes and crustaceans
Body and fins are red with many small blue spots scattered on body. The dorsal edge of the caudal peduncle has 2 prominent black spots.

Red Grouper

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Red Grouper
Epinephelus morio

The scientific genus name â€œEpinephelusâ€ is derived from the Greek word â€œepinephelosâ€ meaning cloudy
Common throughout the Atlantic Ocean from North Carolina so Southern Brazil including the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean Sea.
Found in areas with muddy and rocky bottom habitats where they rest on the bottom substrate.
The head and body are dark reddish brown in color with light colored blotches and spots scattered on the body
Groupers have several sets of strong, slender teeth that are used to prevent small fish from escaping instead of tearing flesh
Prey items include crabs, shrimp, octopi, and small fish
Known to ambush prey and swallow it whole
Females reach sexual maturity at 4-6 years and males at 10 years of age.
Can reach up to 51 pounds and have a lifespan of 25-30 years.
A protogynous hermaphrodite, all fish start life as females with most transforming to males between the ages of 7-14 years.
Spawning occurs from January to April in the Gulf of Mexico and Caribbean Sea.
Eggs and sperm are released into offshore waters where fertilized eggs will float on the waterâ€™s surface
Predators include sharks and barracudas

Common in the western Atlantic from Massachusetts to Brazil including the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean and in the eastern Atlantic down the coast of Africa.
Usually found in solitude inhabiting rocky reefs.
Feed on crabs and fishes in the western Atlantic and on baby sea turtles and triggerfish in the eastern Atlantic
Coloration is tan with red spots on the head, body, and fins with the spots becoming larger ventrally
A powerful suction is created when they open their mouths, easily sucking in prey items and swallowing them whole
Like other groupers, all begin life as females and change to males as they mature.

  • SeaTube

Blue Angelfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Blue Angelfish
Holacanthus bermudensis

Maximum length: 18 inches

Benthic fish, they stay near the bottom to feed on sponges, corals, and algae
Can hybridize with Queen Angelfish
Juveniles set up â€œcleaning stationsâ€, picking parasites off of larger fish
Common in the tropical parts of the Western Atlantic and the Gulf of Mexico
Have small protractile mouths and comb like teeth
Moves around the reef during the day and sleeps hidden away at night
Has a blue smudge on its forehead and a blue caudal (tail) fin bordered in yellow
Adults are generally found in pairs year round, suggesting a monogamous relationship between the male and the female

French Angelfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

French Angelfish
Pomacanthus paru

Maximum length is 24 inches while common length is 16 inches

Commonly found in the western Atlantic Ocean from Florida and the Bahamas, south to Brazil including the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean Sea.
Usually found at depths less than 15 feet in coral reef areas.
Have small mouths with comb-like teeth
Their scales are black and rimmed with a bright golden yellow. They have black fins with yellow bars at the base of the pectoral fins, yellow rimmed eyes, and a white chin
Juveniles are dark brown to black with three thick vertical yellow bands that continue onto the fins.
Angelfish may live up to 10 years
Sexual maturity is reached at lengths of 10 inches
Feed on a wide range of algae and invertebrates
Juveniles feed on algae and detritus along with ectoparasites they clean from other fishes.
Tend â€œcleaning stationsâ€ where they remove ectoparasites from a wide range of fishes including jacks, snappers, morays, grunts, surgeonfishes, and wrasses.
Spawning occurs from April through September over deep reef areas in the early morning hours. During each event, approximately 25,000-75,000 eggs are released.
The eggs are pelagic
Large fish are potential predators

  • Can be found in:
  • SeaTube

Green Moray Eel

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Green Moray Eel
Gymnothorax funebris

Maximum length is 72 inches

Can weigh up to 30 pounds
Move by undulating their flattened bodies into lateral waves
Are constantly opening and closing their mouths to force water over the gills
Commonly found in shallow, rocky shorelines, reefs, and mangroves in the western Atlantic from New Jersey to Brazil.
Have scale free skin that is bathed in a protective, yellowy mucus that tints them green and protects them from parasites and diseases
Often hide in rock crevices and caves where they hide from predators and wait for unsuspecting prey.
Are able to tie themselves in knots to gain leverage for tearing prey
Hunt at night and feed on crabs, cephalopods, shrimps, and fishes
Rely on their keen sense of smell to locate prey
They have 2 rows of single cuspid teeth on the front of their upper jaw and one row in the back and along the lower jaw. The roof of the mouth has 2 rows of teeth.
Eels are oviparous, meaning they produce eggs that hatch outside of the body.

  • Can be found in:
  • Cave Exhibit
  • SeaTube

Bluestriped Grunt

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Bluestriped Grunt
Haemulon sciurus


Maximum length is 18 inches
Found in the western Atlantic Ocean from South Carolina to Brazil. This includes the Gulf of Mexico and Caribbean Sea.
Common in mangroves, reefs, and seagrass beds
Known to occasionally face and push one another with open mouths. The purpose of this behavior is unknown but it may be related to courtship or territory defense.
Named for the pig-like grunts produced with their well-developed pharyngeal teeth located in the throat. They grind the teeth together to produce the sound which is amplified by the taut air bladder
Feed on crustaceans, bivalves, and various small fishes
Spawn during the months of January-April in the Caribbean Sea.

  • Can be found in:
  • SeaTube

Up

French Grunt

Menu
Click to enlarge.

French Grunt
Haemulon flavolineatum

Maximum length is 11.8 inches while common length is 6.7 inches

Commonly found in the western Atlantic Ocean off Bermuda, South Carolina and the northern Gulf of Mexico to Brazil
Occur in large schools over rocky substrate, coral reefs, under ledges or close to elkhorn coral.
Juveniles are commonly found in bays and lagoons where they can find protection in sea grass beds
Identified from other grunts because they are the only grunt that has enlarged scales below the lateral line
Coloration is white to bluish with bright yellow to orange stripes. The first 3 stripes are straight, with the stripes below the lateral line being diagonal
All grunts are able to grind their teeth together to produce a grunting noise that is amplified by the swim bladder
Feeds primarily on small crustaceans, polychaetes, and mollusks
Considered a nocturnal species, scavenges sea beds at night.
Predators include trumpetfish, black grouper, and Nassau grouper

  • Can be found in:
  • SeaTube

Brown Bullhead Catfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Brown Bullhead Catfish
Amerius nebulosus

Common length: 8- 16 inches

Largest and least common bullhead species in Ohio
Prefer deep, clear waters
Sharp spines on dorsal and pectoral fins
Build nests in natural cavities where females will lay eggs
At least one of the parents will guard the eggs until they hatch
Males guard the young after they hatch
Feed on fish, crayfish, and aquatic insects

  • Ohio Gamefish

Channel Catfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Channel Catfish
Ictalurus punctatus

Common length: 15 - 25 inches

A popular sport and food fish
Found in large rivers and lakes throughout Ohio
Prefer areas with deep water, clean gravel, and low currents but tolerant of a wide range of conditions
Use natural cavities, such as undercut banks and burrows, as nests to lay eggs in
Scaleless and have a spine in the pectoral and dorsal fins
Eight barbels around the mouth are used for locating food
Omnivores, eat a variety of foods including insect larvae, crayfish, mollusks, fish, and some types of fruits

  • Can be found in:
  • Ohio Gamefish

Up

African Spurred Tortoise

Menu
Click to enlarge.

African Spurred Tortoise
Geochelone sulcata

Average Size: 20 inches and 70-100 pounds

Third largest land tortoise worldwide

Lifespan in the wild is 50 - 70 years

Found in Sub-Saharan Africa, across the countries of Burkina Faso, Chad, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Mali, Mauritania, Nigeria, Senegal and Sudan

Herbivores, feeding on wild grasses and plants in their native range.

In captivity they will feed on any vegetation available, here they get a variety of vegetables.

Males can be identified by having a concave plastron and anal scutes that are more flared or forked than females.

Common name refers to the well-defined spurs on the legs

In the 1990â€™s this species of tortoise became popular pets in the U.S. and as a result, captive raised animals became readily available to the public. They are now recognized as the most produced tortoise species in the world.

This boom in popularity was not accompanied with appropriate education for the new pet owners. Many found themselves quickly overwhelmed with the needs of housing and caring for such large and fast growing animals.

An overpopulation of this species has occurred at rescue facilities around the country as pet owners have tried to get rid of their once small tortoises.


*Our tortoises are rescue animals from Noahâ€™s Lost Ark, an exotic animal sanctuary that provides a permanent and safe home to unwanted and abused animals

  • Can be found in:
  • African Spurred Tortoise

Australian Side-Necked Turtle

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Australian Side-Necked Turtle
Chelodina longicollis

Maximum size: 7 inches (shell length)
Maximum weight: 2 pounds

Endemic to Eastern and South Eastern Australia

Lifespan is 31 - 37 years

Semi-aquatic, typically found in swamps, lakes, and slow-moving waterways and creeks

Carnivorous, feed on aquatic invertebrates, fish, tadpoles, crustaceans, plankton and carrion

Can emit a pungent musk to deter predators

Have good water storage abilities which allow them to go dormant under trees in forested habitats for long periods

Identified by a long narrow neck covered in short tubercles and a black to light brown oval carapace that contains a central groove

During times of breeding, males perform head bobbing and fast swimming in an attempt to gain the attention of females

  • Can be found in:
  • Australia Side-Necked Turtles

Archerfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Archerfish
Toxotes jaculatrix

Maximum size: 10 inches

Inhabit fresh and salt waters of Southeast Asia (India, New Guinea, Australia, Philippines, Southeast Asia, and Oceania)

Found in Mangrove swamps

Can survive in salt water and fresh water

Found at or near the top of the water column

Typically found in schools

Hunt by shooting insects out of the air with spouts of water from their mouth

Can shoot prey up to 4 feet away

Occasionally they will jump from the water to pick insects out of mid flight

Can control their vision so that they can see from water to air without refraction of water and air, eliminating distortions

  • Can be found in:
  • Asia Archerfish

Bahama Sea Star

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Bahama Sea Star
Oreaster reticulatus

Maximum Length: 19.5 inches

Use water pressure for circulation, instead of blood

Are able to regurgitate their stomachs out of their mouths in order to digest large prey items

Lay a large amount of buoyant eggs in water currents, external fertilization occurs

Live in solitude

Active during the day, using thousands of tube feet to move about 0.12-0.33 m per minute.

Ranges from South Carolina to the Caribbean

Distinguished from other species by their hard shell and short tapered arms

Coloration can range from brown and red to orange and yellow.

Juveniles are green, this provides camouflage from predators

If food availability is low, they can re-absorb their own tissue leading to a reduction in size

Can sense light and dark through a microscopic eye called an ocellus

Feed on small invertebrates such as copepods, crab larvae, sponge tissue, and worms.

  • Can be found in:
  • Echinoderms
  • Touch Pool Invertibrates

Blue Boxfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Blue Boxfish
Ostracion meleagris

Maximum Length: 6 inches

Boxfish belong to the Ostraciidae family.
Inhabit the waters of the Indo-Pacific region, usually clear lagoons and seaweed reefs
Males swim about more openly than females which are often in close vicinity to the males. They are commonly found in solitude
Exhibit sexual dimorphism, females and juveniles are brown or green with white spots. Large males are blue with orange spots or bands.
A boxfishesâ€™ scales form hexagonal bony plates that are fused together to form a rigid body case that is bell shaped and inflexible.
Only the eyes, jaws, and fins are mobile
Feed on tunicates, polychaetes, sponges, mollusks, copepods, and algae.

  • Can be found in:
  • Hawaiian Fish

Clown Anemonefish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Clown Anemonefish
Amphiprion ocellaris

Maximum length: 4 inches

Bright orange with three white vertical bars
Found in the Indian Ocean, Red Sea, and Western Pacific
Share a symbiotic relationship with sea anemones. The sea anemone protects the clownfish from predators and the
A slime coating protects them from the stinging tentacles of the sea anemone
All clownfish develop first into males and then possibly into females later.
An adult male and female may reside on the same anemone with several juveniles. If the female dies, the largest male will transform into a female.
Females control males with aggressive dominance
Monogamous, mate for life
Males guard and aerate the eggs which adhere to substrate

  • Can be found in:
  • Live Coral
  • Hermit Crab

Common Goldfish
Carassius auratus

Maximum Length: 16 inches, typically 6-10 inches

Feed on invertebrates, some algae, and plant material

Are an invasive species to the United States
Native only to Asia
Invasive species are defined as non-native species to the ecosystem that creates a negative impact on our natural environment.
Human actions, such as travels, export shipping, or releasing exotic pets, are the primary reasons for invasive species to be introduced.

Up

Crevalle Jack

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Crevalle Jack
Caranx hippos

Maximum length is 39.8 inches
Found in the coastal areas of the western Atlantic Ocean from Nova Scotia to Uruguay and the Gulf of Mexico.
Found in oceans, estuaries, and rivers.
Larval and juveniles are found in upstream currents and are common in shallow brackish waters.
Adults occupy upstream currents, reefs, offshore areas or shallow inshore areas.
Identified by their scaleless chest with a small patch of scales in front of the pelvic fins and an oval black spot on the pectoral fins
Juveniles have 5 dark bars on their bodies until the reach about 6.5 inches.
Adults are greenish-bluish above and silvery white to yellowish or golden below.
Make a croaking sound when out of the water by grinding their upper and lower teeth together.
Feed on a variety of fish, shrimp, and invertebrates.
Spawn in early March to early September in the southeastern Atlantic coast and in the Gulf Stream.
Predators include surface feeding carnivores such as the striped marlin and sea birds.

  • SeaTube

Up

Gulf Flounder

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Gulf Flounder
Paralichthys albigutta

Maximum size: 71 cm

Flounder swim sideways which makes it easier for them to bury themselves with a thin layer of sand. They use a fluttering motion to do this.
Flounder camouflage themselves in the sand but have 3 eye-like spots on their side that form a triangle.
Both of the gulf flounderâ€™s eyes are on the same side of its body. This feature allows it to stay buried flat in the sand while also looking for prey.
It hatches into a usual fish form, but the right eye eventually migrates over to the left side.
They are predators who lie on the sandy bottom, waiting for a small prey species to come by. By having both eyes on one side of the head, a degree of depth perception is generated that enables them to swim up and capture the prey. The upper side of the fish, on which the eyes are found, is dark-colored, to match the bottom, but the underside is whitish-pink. And there are "right-eyed" and "left-eyed" flounders, depending on which side of the head the eyes migrate to!

  • Can be found in:
  • Rock Pool
  • Menu

  • Home

    Return to the home page.

  • Scanner

    Scan a QR code to go directly to an exhibit's page.

  • Map

    View a map of the aquarium.

  • Search

    Find what you're looking for.

Lined Seahorse

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Lined Seahorse
Hippocampus erectus

Maximum size: 8 inches

Found in shallow seagrass beds, coral reefs, and floating sargassum from Nova Scotia to Argentina and throughout the Gulf of Mexico
Swim upright by rapidly fluttering a small fin on their back
Tails curl around the vegetation or coral branches to anchor them in place and conserve energy
Do not have stomachs, so they eat frequently using their tubular snout to suck in tiny crustaceans
Monogamous species pairing for life
One of the few species where the males become pregnant and give birth

  • Can be found in:
  • Seahorses

Lionfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Lionfish
Pterois volitans

Found in the Indian and Western Pacific oceans
Characterized by red, white and black bands, showy pectoral fins and venomous spines
Spines contain venom which is used as a defense mechanism
Aggressively prey on small fish and invertebrates as they hide in crevices and then ambush prey as it swims past
Predators of the lionfish are larger fish, eels, and humans
Live up to 15 years
In the mid 1990s two species were unintentionally introduced into the Atlantic Ocean and have become an invasive species along the East Coast of the United States

  • Can be found in:
  • Lionfish

Lookdown

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Lookdown
Selene vomer

Maximum length is 16 inches
Have a very blunt forehead and an extremely deep and laterally compressed body with very small, embedded scales
Coloration is iridescent silvery to golden with a metallic bluish tinge on the dorsal side
Occur in shallow coastal waters over sand or mud in the western Atlantic from Maine to Uruguay, including Bermuda
Travel in schools
Feed near the bottom on crustaceans and other fishes
Named for the way they appear to look down their noses

  • Can be found in:
  • Coastal Arch
  • SeaTube

Oyster Toadfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Oyster Toadfish
Osparius tau

Maximum length: 12 inches

Has a scaleless, flattened body that is olive-brown, black with dark blotches and bars.
Fleshy flaps or whiskers on cheeks and jaws
Can tolerate litter and polluted water, and can survive out of water for a lengthy period of time.
Defends itself from predators with strong, broad jaws, full of rounded teeth and a spiny dorsal fin.
A bottom dweller found primarily around oyster reefs, it can also be found in wrecks, debris, vegetation, and other dark spots in shallow waters in warmer weather
In cooler months it moves into the deep channels of the Chesapeake Bay.

  • Can be found in:
  • Porkfish

Porkfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Porkfish
Anisotremus virginicus

Maximum length: 15 inches

Commonly found in the Atlantic Ocean from Florida to Brazil
Nocturnal
Often found in schools inhabiting shallow inshore waters over reefs and rocky bottoms
Make a grunting sound by rubbing their teeth together
Has yellow fins and 2 black bars, one of which runs diagonally through the eye
Adults feed on invertebrates such as mollusks, echinoderms, and worms.
Juveniles pick parasites from the skin and scales of other species of fish, and are considered "cleaners".

  • Can be found in:
  • Porkfish

Red-Bellied Piranha

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Red-Bellied Piranha
Pygocentrus nattereri

Inhabit fast flowing river systems in South America
A single row of sharp, interlocking teeth in both jaws are used for rapid puncture and shearing of prey
Average length is 8 - 15 inches
More than 30 different species of Piranha have been identified
Known for their voracious appetite for meat, but are actually omnivores
Feed on fish, snails, insects and aquatic plants occasionally eating larger mammals and birds
Form large schools and constantly compete for food
Predators include river dolphins, crocodiles, turtles, birds, larger fish, and humans

  • Can be found in:
  • Red Bellied Piranha

Redside Dace

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Redside Dace
Clinostomus elongatus

The redside dace is a species of ray-finned fish in the Cyprinidae family, found in the United States and Canada. They are commonly found in small, clear, cool streams. They are unique among minnows, being the only species to routinely feed on flying insects by leaping from water. Thus, it acts as a conduit for nutrient transfers between terrestrial and aquatic environments. The species can be used as an ecosystem health indicator, as it is sensitive to environmental disturbances.

  • Can be found in:
  • Ohio River 1

Found throughout the Caribbean Sea, Atlantic and Pacific Oceans

River Chub

Menu
Click to enlarge.

River Chub
Nocomis micropogon

A robust minnow, dark olivaceous above to dusky yellow below, with orange-red fins, large scales, a large slightly subterminal mouth, and a small barbel at the corners of the jaw. During the breeding season, sexually mature males develop pinkish-purple coloration, and swollen heads with tubercles between the eyes and snout tip.

  • Can be found in:
  • Ohio River 1

Rooster Hogfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Rooster Hogfish
Lachnolaimus maximus

Maximum length is 36 inches
Commonly found in the Western Atlantic from North Carolina down to the north coast of South America, including the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean Sea
Commonly found over open bottoms and coral reefs and prefers locations with hard sand and rock bottoms near shallow patch reefs.
Get their name from their elongate, pig-like snout and large protrusible mouth that it uses to root around the bottom substrate for prey.
Generally, coloration is from pearl white to mottled in brownish-red with a black spot at the rear base of the soft dorsal fin and a bright red iris.
Males tend to be more intensely colored.
Have strong jaws and protruding anterior canine teeth
These teeth are adapted for crushing the shells of prey items such as mollusks and crabs
Have been known to live for up to 11 years
Hogfish are protogynous hermaphrodites. Females can transform into fully functioning males after they reach a mature size
Hogfish schools consist of groups of females dominated by a larger male, referred to as a harem. The male guards his harem and spawns exclusively with the females within it.
Spawning usually occurs in later afternoon and early evening.
Males and females release gametes into the surrounding water where they are fertilized.
Predators include larger bony fish and sharks

  • Can be found in:
  • SeaTube

Saddleback Butterflyfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Saddleback Butterflyfish
Chaetodon ephippium

Found in the Indo-Pacific region
Overall coloration is yellowish-grey with a large black spot bordered below by a white band on the back and wavy blue lines on the lower sides
Adults have a filament extending from the upper part of the front portion of the dorsal fin
Found in lagoons and seaward reefs where they prefer coral-rich and clear water areas
Adults are often found in pairs and juveniles are found solitary
Feed on algae, small invertebrates, coral polyps and fish eggs
Maximum length is 12 inches

  • Can be found in:
  • Indo-Pacific Lagoon

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Shovelnose Sturgeon
Scaphirhynchus platorynchus

Have armored plates rather than scales and a broad, flat snout that gives them their name
Females reach sexual maturity at 5 years and do not spawn every year
Were commonly found in the Ohio River until 1910 when the lock and dam systems were built; now are an endangered species
Common length is 18-30 inches

  • Can be found in:
  • Ohio River 2 (Sturgeon)

Southern Redbelly Dace

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Southern Redbelly Dace
Phoxinus erythrogaster

The Southern redbelly dace, is a North American species of temperate freshwater fish of the Cyprinidae family. The natural geographic range extends from Western New York to Minnesota, and south to Oklahoma, Arkansas, and Alabama.This fish prefers flowing pools of creeks and streams.The bellies of breeding males are entirely red.

When breeding, they have distinct pairing and are oviparous

Greenish brown with black along their sides

Upside Down Jellyfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Upside Down Jellyfish
Cassiopea xamachana

  • The bell is positioned downwards while the tentacles are upwards in the water column
  • Found on the bottom of inshore bays and mangrove forests throughout the Caribbean Sea, Gulf of Mexico, Hawaii and Indo-Pacific Oceans
  • Lifecycle consists of four phases, which are larva, polyp, ephyra, and medusa
  • Nematocysts, or stinging cells, cover the tentacles and are used for both feeding and defense
  • Maximum width is 12 inches

  • Can be found in:
  • Upside-Down Jellyfish

White Cloud Mountain Minnow

Menu
Click to enlarge.

White Cloud Mountain Minnow
Tanichthys albonubes

Native to White Cloud Mountain located a few miles north of the city of Guangzhou in China
Inhabits clear, slow moving brooks with thick weed growth where they feed on plankton and the larvae of aquatic insects

  • Can be found in:
  • Asian River

Yellow Blotch Rabbitfish

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Yellow Blotch Rabbitfish
Siganus guttatus

Native to the Indo-Pacific Region inhabiting inshore reefs among mangroves.
Can tolerate waters with low salinities
Feeds on benthic algae
Active at night
Venomous dorsal spines that it will raise when disturbed, uses them as defense.
Called a rabbitfish because of the shape of its nose
Has a yellow spot at the base of its dorsal fin , just before the caudal peduncle (tail)
Maximum Length is 16 inches

  • Can be found in:
  • Indo-Pacific Lagoon

Yellow Perch
Perca flavescens

Found in clear lakes, reservoirs, and slow streams
Gold to green in color with 6 â€“ 8 dark vertical bars
Feed on aquatic insects, invertebrates and small fish
Common length is 5 - 16 inches

Yellow Rainbow

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Yellow Rainbow
Melanotaenia hebertaxelrodi

Native to Lake Tebera basin in Papua New Guinea
Males are larger, have deeper bodies, brighter coloration, and longer dorsal fins than females
Omnivorous
Maximum length 3.5 inches

  • Can be found in:
  • Australia Rainbowfish

Yellowtail Damsel

Menu
Click to enlarge.

Yellowtail Damsel
Chrysiptera parasema

Maximum Length 3 inches
Found in Western Pacific in coral rich habitats
Omnivore, feeding on vegetation and small invertebrates.
Semi-aggressive
Have a bright blue body and yellow tail

  • Can be found in:
  • Hawaiian Fish
